le capital, innovative ideas, a mutable future: movement is omnipresent. In modern society, movement not only forms an antipole to stagnation or immobility, but also develops its very own dynamic to shape society socially, culturally and materially. The contributions in this volume observe "movement" from various sociological perspectives and on the basis of various case studies from automobility to the physical movement of children and social innovations. The diversity of this sociologically stretched horizon inspires agility: in thinking about "movement".  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aSociology. 4aBeobachtung. 4aBewegung. 4aEinführung. 4aEmpirie. 4aGesellschaft. 4aKultur. 4aKultursoziologie. 4aMobilität. 4aPolitische Soziologie. 4aSozialität. 4aSoziologische Theorie. 4aTheorie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aEmpirical Research.  aIntroduction.  aMobility.  aMovement.  aObservation.  aPolitical Sociology.  aSocial Relations.  aSociety.  aSociological Theory.  aSociology of Culture.  aTheory.1 aBurkart, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanzler, Weert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrews, Nikolai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDöpking, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarzin, Sina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreve, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenkel, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenkel, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHobuß, Steffi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaut, Manuela